can connect a vintage or retro rotary phone to your cell phone in two main ways: using a Bluetooth-to-landline adapter to use an actual antique phone, or buying a modern retro Bluetooth rotary phone.1. Connect an Original Rotary Phone to Your Cell PhoneIf you already have a classic rotary phone, you can convert it to work with your smartphone using a cellular gateway adapter. This allows you to make and receive calls on your smartphone using the rotary handset and dial.How it works: You plug the rotary phone into the adapter, and the adapter pairs via Bluetooth to your cell phone. When you get a call, the rotary phone rings.Top Adapters:Cell2Jack: A popular, budget-friendly option (typically $35–$50) that plugs directly into your rotary phone and connects via Bluetooth to your cell.XLink BT HD: Generally receives top ratings from users for being reliable and supporting older pulse-dialing systems well (usually around $65).2. Buy a Modern Rotary Phone with Built-In BluetoothIf you don’t have a vintage phone but want the aesthetic, you can purchase modern, ready-to-use rotary phones that have Bluetooth and rechargeable batteries built in.How it works: These are plug-and-play devices that pair wirelessly with your iOS or Android device just like a standard Bluetooth headset or speaker.Options: Many retailers sell these modern Bluetooth rotary phones online, typically priced between $70 and $115. You can browse available models on platforms like Amazon's Bluetooth Rotary Phone Selection or eBay's Vintage and Bluetooth Rotary Market.3. Build a "Riotary" Cell PhoneFor a completely custom, portable solution, some tech hobbyists use microcontrollers (like a Raspberry Pi) and a cellular module to gut an old rotary phone and turn it into a standalone mobile phone. However, this requires soldering, coding, and basic electronics knowledge.
